I pored over the numbers, unsure what to make of them. &ldquo;So explain, snotnose&rdquo; I grumbled. Somehow this venture did not feel entirely mine any more.
&ldquo;It&rsquo;s like this,&rdquo; the vixen explained, slightly patronizingly I felt, &ldquo;We did a number of books as seeds to see how things went differently depending on your starting point.&rdquo;
&ldquo;But some have the same book name.&rdquo;
&ldquo;That&rsquo;s because each bookshop may go different ways, depending on what choices the cat tells you to make, and we wanted to see if the results depended a lot on what book you start with. So would you always get the same shop if you start with one book.&rdquo;
&ldquo;And do you?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Sometimes yes, sometimes no. Like, we did Our Mutual Friend twice because we both did Charles Dickens at school and hated it. Can&rsquo;t that man say anything in less than twenty pages? And you can see that one of them ended up with a median of 2471 and one with a median of over 7,000. That&rsquo;s quite a difference on this list. And we did The Long Tail quite a few times because Mr. Amazon told me about that when I asked him how he could help The Adventures of Wazzock to get what it deserves. But in the end, with a few exceptions it doesn&rsquo;t make much difference what book you start with. You&rsquo;ll spend at least half your time in the top 10,000 books, which is like browsing around the heavy traffic area of a regular bookshop. And you&rsquo;ll spend almost all your time in the top 100,000, so you don&rsquo;t really see much that you wouldn&rsquo;t see in a normal bookshop.&rdquo;
&ldquo;What about these exceptions you mention?&rdquo;
&ldquo;There are three that are different, and all for the same reason. Look at these bottom three in the list. The Secret History, Last Best Gifts, and The Dilbert Principle.&rdquo;
&ldquo;What about them?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Well The Dilbert Principle is the book that spends most of its time out in the outsider part of the shop, beyond the 100 grand mark. Any idea why?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Well I have heard that Dilbert is an humorous illustration of some kind. Isn&rsquo;t that right?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Yeah, so what you get is, you bounce around a lot of other comic books. Every one of the top 14 books is a Dilbert book and from what I can tell all but two of the top 80 are comics. There&rsquo;s not really any one big bestseller in comics, so that&rsquo;s why you spend so much time in the outsider books.&rdquo;
&ldquo;And what about Last Best Gifts?&rdquo;
&ldquo;A bit different. It&rsquo;s basically an academic book and you end up going round a lot of other academic books. You don&rsquo;t always do that - like Graph Theory is pretty much like a bestseller - but Last Best Gifts seems to just wander the academic ghetto. What a bunch of losers!&rdquo;
&ldquo;And The Secret History?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Now that one is very strange.&rdquo; Kylie frowned and scratched her stomach, contemplating the oddities of the world. &ldquo;This shop has the least number of books of all. Ten thousand different views and there&rsquo;s only 14 different books in the lot! The reason is that early on it gets into books by this bloke Christopher Moore who, it says here, writes offbeat humour. And then all the recommendations are for other Christopher Moore books. And the really odd thing is that none of those books appear in any of the other bookshops. You either like Christopher Moore or you don&rsquo;t I guess.&rdquo;
&ldquo;So what have we learned?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Well, first that it&rsquo;s really easy to get distracted by these little stories of what makes one bookshop different from another.&rdquo;
&ldquo;And second?&rdquo;
&ldquo;That&rsquo;ll have to wait until tomorrow. I&rsquo;m hungry and I&rsquo;m going to steal some lunch.&rdquo; And with that she stalked, hands deep in pockets, down the drive towards the village.

[This is the tenth episode of Mr. Amazon&rsquo;s Bookshop. There will probably be another five or six before I&rsquo;m done. A list of all episodes is here; the previous episode is here.]
I rang for Google who, as so often, appeared quicker than seemed reasonable, with his usual false air of subservience.
&ldquo;How the hell do you get here so quickly Google?&rdquo; I demanded, slightly taken aback by the speed with which he materialized at my shoulder.
&ldquo;Oh, nothing special sir - I just keep a copy of myself close by in case you need anything. It may seem a little unusual, but it&rsquo;s entirely neutral. Any other butler could do the same. Certainly no one is leveraging their unilateral control over your bell to hamper user choice, competition, and innovation.&rdquo;
I often regret asking too many questions of Google. I never know when he is being funny and when he&rsquo;s not. Usually I decide to treat his remarks as humour because life is just easier that way, but he has an excellent poker face so it&rsquo;s hard to tell.
&ldquo;Well, never mind. Listen, we have some questions for you. It&rsquo;s about Mr. Amazon.&rdquo;
Google&rsquo;s face showed an instant distaste: &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll do what I can.&rdquo;
I was just searching for the best way to phrase my questions when Kylie piped up.
&ldquo;Hey Mr. G. We&rsquo;re trying to find out whether Mr. Amazon&rsquo;s recommendations are going to help me to sell lots of copies of The Adventures of Wazzock. We need to know some things about Mr. Amazon&rsquo;s sales. Like how much he sells that you couldn&rsquo;t get in a regular establishment bookshop.&rdquo; She spat at Edmund as she said this last sentence.
&ldquo;A fine question young miss. Let&rsquo;s see. I am ashamed to say I know very little about Mr. Amazon&rsquo;s sales in any detail. I have means to find out many things, but he seems capable of great secrecy. But from what I hear it is possible that he makes about 25% of his sales from books beyond the 100,000 mark. Such measurement depends greatly, of course, on what length of time the sales ranks are averaged over. A book that is positioned at 150,000 could easily put itself into the top 100,000 by a single sale - so do you count the sale as before or after the purchase? Still, I imagine the figure is not too far from the truth.&rdquo;
&ldquo;When it comes to real bookshops, a small independent bookshop may stock 30,000 titles. But of course they sell special orders too. Perhaps ten percent of their sales are special orders. A large chain store like Heather&rsquo;s Big House O&rsquo;Books may stock 100,000 titles. But there are larger ones still. I am told that Blackwells in Oxford, for example, stocks above 200,000 distinct titles in its shops on The Broad.&rdquo;
&ldquo;You&rsquo;re a gem Mr. G. That&rsquo;s what we need to know.&rdquo;
&ldquo;It is?&rdquo; I asked.
&ldquo;Obviously&rdquo;, said Kylie. &ldquo;Think a bit. He makes one sale in every four from outside the top 100 grand books. But when he mutters his &lsquo;would you be interested&rsquo; guff, we look at these outsider books only about once in eight times. So he&rsquo;s pushing the top sellers, innit? He&rsquo;s only selling them others because he&rsquo;s a convenient way to order books you already know about, which is probably just taking business from the regular bookshops where you might have ordered them before. And quit the boozing, we&rsquo;ve got work to do.&rdquo;
It took a moment before I realized she was talking to me. I sheepishly replaced the cap on the flask of cognac and returned it to my overcoat pocket.
&ldquo;Hey shortbus,&rdquo; Kylie was approaching Edmund, who flinched. &ldquo;Let&rsquo;s have a look at that other graph of yours. What&rsquo;s it show?
Later on that day I managed to get a look at the graph, which I reproduce below. Meanwhile, Kylie was telling us all about it.
&ldquo;So if I read this right, you&rsquo;ve got your views of a book up the side, and your sales rank along the bottom. And most of the books Mr. Amazon shows us are bunched up at the left among the mainstream establishment junk, which we knew already. But it also shows that the ones he shows many times lot are almost all best sellers. Look at them buggers that have come up more than 50 times! Let&rsquo;s see&rdquo; (she scoured the notebook again, brow furiously furrowed.) &ldquo;There&rsquo;s 31 books that we looked at over 50 times. Twenty three of those 31 are in the top grand. All but two of them is in the top two grand. And I bet not one of them is The Adventures of Wazzock. He&rsquo;s just showing everyone the establishment books innit? I thought he was all friendly to us kids, but it looks like he&rsquo;s just like the bastard publishers! I should have known. He&rsquo;s all about the money. What an absolute pillock.&rdquo; She spat on the ground as she said this.
Such was her virulence I confess that I actually felt sorry for Mr. Amazon, who is after all just trying to make a living.
&ldquo;Let&rsquo;s not leap to conclusions young Kylie. After all, this is just one sample, like you said. Maybe if we set up the differ again and start with another one, we&rsquo;ll see something different. And would you like an ice cream?&rdquo;
Her expression remained ominously grim.
&ldquo;I&rsquo;m not being bought off with no ice cream. But you&rsquo;re right Mr. W. We&rsquo;ll have to try again. I&rsquo;ll be back tomorrow morning. You be ready or else, numskull.&rdquo; She kicked Edmund affectionately in the shins as she stomped off back down the drive.

