I could hardly believe my bleary eyes when I entered the stable the next day &ndash; young Edmund was there already, sitting at the trestle table next to the differ controls, with my private notebook open in front of him! He may smudge it with his grubby gardener fingers, or drip his slimy gardener snot over my pages! I swatted him across the back of the hands with my switch (I always carry a switch). &ldquo;Enough of that lad! What do you think you&rsquo;re doing? Don&rsquo;t meddle in matters you don&rsquo;t understand.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Sorry Mr. Whimsley sir. I was just thinking, that&rsquo;s all. And drawing.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Drawing! Drawing what?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Well, you were thinking about them books, right?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Yes, to put it simplistically, I concede you could say that.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Well, I drew some graphs for you. I like graphs. They have colours.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Graphs of what, you idiot? I do hope you&rsquo;ve not been messing up my notebook!&rdquo;
&ldquo;Oh no sir. Here they are, in my own scrapbook.&rdquo; He put a great big book onto the table and showed me. I was stunned: the airhead was apparently not entirely stupid. Here is what I saw.
I could not immediately discern what the graph was saying, so I demanded: &ldquo;Explain this to me Edmund!&rdquo;
&ldquo;Well sir, I&rsquo;m not entirely sure, but I was looking at this last night and it seems to me that you can use a graph like this to say something about whether Mr. Amazon is making culture more democratic or not. You know, like Kylie says.&rdquo;
&ldquo;You know that scold Kylie? How on earth?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Yes sir. At least, when we&rsquo;re at school she always beats me up and takes my lunch money from me, and even though it&rsquo;s summer holidays she turned up at my house yesterday because she said she was bored and wanted a reason to be pissed off at someone. I was looking at your notebook so she just took it. She&rsquo;s a bit like that.&rdquo;
&ldquo;I had noticed. But wait a minute! You had my notebook? What kind of effrontery is that?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Well, judging from how loud you were snoring and the level of the scotch bottle on the table in the conservatory you weren&rsquo;t going to be needing it, so I thought I might be able to help you a little.&rdquo;
I brandished the switch, but restrained myself.
&ldquo;Tell me the rest, vagabond.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Well Kylie, she looks at it, and she says &lsquo;This is T&rsquo;owd Git&rsquo;s innit?&lsquo;&rdquo;
&ldquo;T&rsquo;owd Git?&rdquo;
&ldquo;That&rsquo;s what we all call you in the village. I&rsquo;m not sure what it means. Something like &ldquo;his lordship&rdquo; but more affectionate I think. Anyway, she stared at it for some time and muttered to herself and then looked at me and said in this really grim voice, &lsquo;The median salesrank is crap. And the distribution is scanty. There are too many repeats here. Something&rsquo;s not right.&rsquo; Then she gave it back to me and slapped my on the head.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Median distribution? What could she mean?&rdquo;
&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know sir, but I think she&rsquo;s coming up here soon to talk to you about it. She&rsquo;s not right pleased.&rdquo;
Sure enough, who was coming up the driveway but Kylie, striding purposefully, arms swinging and fingers clenching. She entered the stable and stood, arms crossed, staring pugnaciously up at me.
&ldquo;Well Mr. W. Looks like we have a problem don&rsquo;t it?&rdquo;
&ldquo;What&rsquo;s that, Kylie? This is really too early in the morning for stressful conversations. Can&rsquo;t it wait?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Either you don&rsquo;t know what you&rsquo;re doing with that differ of yours&rdquo; - she gestured dismissively towards my magnificent machine - or Mr. Amazon ain&rsquo;t what I hoped he&rsquo;d be. Now between you and me, guv&rsquo;nor, Mr. Amazon looks a lot more likely to be the goods than you do. But I&rsquo;ve got a lot riding on The Adventures of Wazzock and I need to know for sure. That&rsquo;s why I&rsquo;m here.&rdquo;
&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know what you mean? Amazon is a prim little functionary, while I am a scholar and a gentleman.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Right you are. So he&rsquo;s got an eye on the ready and you&rsquo;re just pissing about, when you&rsquo;re not blotto that is.&rdquo; She nodded at my overcoat pocket, where my cognac flask created, I fear, a slight bulge.
&ldquo;And one other thing. That notebook of yours said it was volume 49 number 11, so I&rsquo;m thinking you do a lot of writing. I bet you&rsquo;re going to write this whole escapade down in one of them notebooks of yours ain&rsquo;t you?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Well, the thought had crossed my mind,&rdquo; I admitted.
&ldquo;Well I bet you make a reet mess of the way I speak. I bet it&rsquo;s nowt like how I sound. I bet you can&rsquo;t even decide what part of the country I come from.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Never mind that, young lady. Back to your visit. I have a proposal.&rdquo;
She raised her left eyebrow quizzically.
&ldquo;Three things. First, you get to take part in my grand inquisition here. I&rsquo;d be lying if I told you that I like Mr. Amazon, but I do want to be fair and you may be able to help balance my enthusiasms.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Fair enough.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Second, you stop taking young Edmund&rsquo;s lunch money.&rdquo; The gormless youngster was positively cowering from Kylie, and a small part of me felt almost protective of the rabbit-like idiot.
&ldquo;No problem. He never has much anyway.&rdquo; She glanced scornfully and dismissively in the oaf&rsquo;s direction. &ldquo;Relax, prat. I&rsquo;ll leave you be.&rdquo; Edmund gave a long and relieved sigh.
&ldquo;And third, you promise to work with us as a team.&rdquo;
&ldquo;No sweat guv&rsquo;nor. Let&rsquo;s get to work. Show me what you&rsquo;ve got.&rdquo;
I brought out my notebook and Edmund&rsquo;s scrapbook. She snatched them both and took them into the corner and stared fixedly at them for ten minutes. I was a little affronted, but Kylie was such a hellion that I dared not interrupt, so I pretended to be inspecting and oiling the differ. Finally, she emerged.
&ldquo;Right Mr. W. First thing. Your method is crap. You obviously have no idea about proper statistics. You look like you&rsquo;re making it up as you go along.&rdquo;
&ldquo;But the differ&hellip;&rdquo;
&ldquo;But let&rsquo;s put that aside. I don&rsquo;t see that other methods are going to give information that&rsquo;s much different. The best way to know what Mr. A. is up to is to look inside his operation, but even I don&rsquo;t know how to do that, so I&rsquo;m sure you haven&rsquo;t got a clue. Without that kind of insider info, this will have to do. The problem is not collecting information, it&rsquo;s knowing what questions you want to ask of it once you&rsquo;ve collected it.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Well why don&rsquo;t you tell me your ideas, since you seem to have such a low opinion of mine.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Right you are then. You&rsquo;ve got a couple of good things, here in this scrapbook. Funny how your handwriting is getting better, and these graphs are very nice. Is this your neat copy or what?&rdquo; Fortunately she did not give me a chance to answer.
&ldquo;This graph. Here&rsquo;s the way I see it. You&rsquo;ve got about 10,000 book views here. That&rsquo;s books Mr. A. has recommended and that you&rsquo;ve picked up to look at. The median sales rank is 2120. That means about half of all the book views in this shop, the one that&rsquo;s grown from Special Topics in Crap Physics or whatever, is spent in the top 2000 sellers. Now 2000 is a small number.&rdquo;
&ldquo;No it ain&rsquo;t,&rdquo; the stunted moron interjected, &ldquo;it&rsquo;s a bloody big number.&rdquo;
Kylie paused. &ldquo;Unbelievably, you may be right, blockhead. First thing we do, we find out how big a number 2000 is. And there are some other numbers too. Four fifths of the time is spent looking at books in the top 30,000. And just over an eighth of the time is spent looking at books outside the top 100,000. So are these big numbers or what?&rdquo;
&ldquo;I believe I can help.&rdquo; I had been caught a little off-balance with this flurry of numbers and thoughts, but righted myself quickly to reassert my natural authority. &ldquo;I have just the person who can tell us these things. My butler is a whiz when it comes to trivia.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Is that Mr. Google?&rdquo; asked Kylie, &ldquo;Yeah, he&rsquo;s smart. Let&rsquo;s go find him and ask.&rdquo;

[This is the seventh instalment of Mr. Amazon&rsquo;s Bookshop. A list of all instalments is here; the previous instalment is here.]
Edmund, the gardener&rsquo;s son, has the look of a runt about him: he is undersized, has a perpetually dripping nose and a habit of scratching his backside. He is looked down on by the Whimsley village children, which is an achievement in itself: he positively broadcasts stupidity. On the other hand, his is obedient and hardworking, which are important qualities in the servant classes, and has a strong pair of arms so I decided to let him assist me with my investigation.
I dragged Edmund out to the stables on a warm July morning, ready to set the differ to work and send more questions to Mr. Amazon, and with a fresh supply of pencils to record the results in my trusty notebook. I set the young halfwit to start the bellows and he soon worked up a healthy pressure. I turned the dials and tugged the pulleys to set my question, and was about to pull the master lever one more time, when Edmund shouted and pointed up at the stable roof. I followed the line of the simpleton&rsquo;s finger, and saw the topmost reaches of my differ perspiring and shivering, as if with fever. The pistons wailed, the cylinders grated, and then the edifice ground to a juddering halt with an earsplitting thud. The differ was obviously damaged and my investigations were going nowhere soon. I kicked Edmund out of the stables in frustration.
For the next month I searched for parts, scoured manuals, and consulted other differ enthusiasts in an attempt to fix my machine. And while I waited for the postman to bring the replies to my questions I did what I could to keep myself occupied. I even cleaned some of the abandoned rooms in Whimsley Hall, myself. The drawing room I restored to, if not exactly its former stateliness, then at least habitability. The worst of the cobwebs and nests were evicted, and with a solution of vinegar and water I attacked the windows so vigorously that light penetrated the room for the first time in years. Thanks to the previous gloom the velvet drapery and the rich colours of the upholstery were unfaded, but the profuse spattering of stains were too ingrained to be removed. I did not mind. They were part, you might say, of the fabric of the place, and each with its own memory.
When I was too tired to work on Whimsley Hall I walked to the village and back, pacing the bounds of the old estate. With head thrust forward, deep in thought, and with a perpetual frown on my face I was doubtless a forbidding site sight, and I was avoided by most villagers.
It was on one of these walks that I was bumped into, literally, by one of the youngsters I had seen around the village - none other than the pugilistic Jane Austen you may recall from a couple of months earlier. I was walking alongside the river, and seized her by the ear as she attempted to barge past on the narrow pathway.
&ldquo;Ow! Leggo! Piss off guv&rsquo;nor!&rdquo; she bawled, in that endearing manner I have come to know so well in the past few months.
&ldquo;Not before you tell me your name, young harridan!&rdquo;
&ldquo;It&rsquo;s Kylie, innit&rdquo; she grunted.
&ldquo;How likely. I&rsquo;m not convinced at all. You know who I am?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Yeah, you&rsquo;re the bloke what lives at the Hall, innit?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Seventh Earl of Whimsley, but I will let is pass. You can call me Mr. Whimsley and I&rsquo;ll call you Kylie for now. Now listen, I have some questions for you. I need answers and I&rsquo;m prepared to pay. Shall we say a hot chocolate at Mr. Horton&rsquo;s? That should pay for fifteen minutes of your time.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Whatever. Just let go of me bloody ear! And stop writin&rsquo; me dialogue in that patronizing phonetic bullshit way. It&rsquo;s not like you speak the way it&rsquo;s written.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Deal. Let&rsquo;s go.&rdquo;
I put her down, and we made our way to Mr. Horton&rsquo;s Coffee Establishment where, once I convinced the proprietor Kylie was not about to steal the contents of the till, we sat and drank a mug of hot chocolate. Kylie was a small and wiry child of about fifteen, with a perpetually sullen expression. I told her that I had overheard her yelling about Mr. Amazon&rsquo;s Bookshop and about her literary ambitions and asked to hear more.
&ldquo;Look, Mr. Whimsley, I like to write. Always have done, ever since looking after my brothers and sisters when they was real young. I made up stories to keep them from ripping the doors off their hinges. Anything to keep the little buggers quiet. So it became a habit, and I reckon I&rsquo;m pretty good at it. But there&rsquo;s no way any of those hi-faluting publishers are going to pay attention to me. I have no education worth speaking of, no contacts to call on&hellip;&rdquo;
&ldquo;And almost certainly no talent. But point taken, go on.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Well, it&rsquo;s like, Mr. Amazon is an odd fish, but I can get the books I like at his shop so I go there sometimes and then one day he told me that if I had written anything I could just give it to him and he&rsquo;d sell it, just like he sells the other books. Isn&rsquo;t that amazing?&rdquo;
&ldquo;It certainly sounds attractive. And have you taken him up on his generous offer?&rdquo;
&ldquo;You bet! I mean, at first I was pretty suspicious and figured he just wanted to rob me of my just rewards, but I had a word with Mr. Anderson - he&rsquo;s a bloke that lives down our street - and he told me it&rsquo;s OK. He said Mr. Amazon&rsquo;s way better than those other bookshops for me because they&rsquo;re all elitist institutions and Mr. Amazon&rsquo;s on my side. He said something else really weird too&hellip;&rdquo; (here she looked around and lowered her voice) &ldquo;He told me that Mr. Amazon&rsquo;s got a long tail. And that made me think I&rsquo;ve only ever seen him from the front, and I can&rsquo;t look over the desk. So maybe it&rsquo;s true! What do you think?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Oh I doubt that&rdquo;, was my first reaction, &ldquo;but come to think of it I, too, see him only from the front. And he does have a certain reptilian quality.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Anyway&rdquo;, Kylie carried on, &ldquo;I finished my book a few weeks ago. It&rsquo;s called The Adventures of Wazzock. It&rsquo;s about a boy who finds a polished blue stone in a mountain chain near his home. He discovers that his stone is really a dragon egg when it hatches suddenly in the night. Wazzock gives his dragon the name Saphira, which he learns from the village storyteller. After the dragon hatches the King sends his servants after Wazzock and Saphira, in an effort to capture or kill them. Wazzock and Saphira flee their hometown and embark on a number of adventures involving swordplay, magic, friendship, betrayal, and death.&rdquo;
&ldquo;I&rsquo;m sure they do. Very good, very good. And how is it going?&rdquo;
&ldquo;It&rsquo;s great. It&rsquo;s only been a few weeks, but I&rsquo;ve already sold five copies.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Really! And who to?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Well, there&rsquo;s my brother and my mum, and then my friend Sharon, and then two boys in my class. Of course, I told them I&rsquo;d beat them up if they didn&rsquo;t buy it. That&rsquo;s called marketing.&rdquo;
&ldquo;And is he selling your book at any of his other shops, or just here in Whimsley?&rdquo;
&ldquo;He&rsquo;s selling it&hellip;&rdquo;, here her voice dropped to a hushed whisper, &ldquo;&hellip;all over the world. Anywhere you go, you could walk into a Mr. Amazon and ask for The Adventures of Wazzock and he&rsquo;ll sell it to you. Right then and there. Isn&rsquo;t that amaaziing??!! It&rsquo;s just me and my audience. No gatekeepers! It&rsquo;s just like Mr. Anderson said. I&rsquo;m alread y working on my next book, so I&rsquo;m ready once Wazzock goes viral.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Admirable. Admirable. Now that&rsquo;s enough young Kylie. I may have need of you again. I have obviously underestimated both you and Mr. Amazon. You have given me much to think on. Off you go.&rdquo;
She grabbed my half-eaten doughnut and waltzed out of the door, looking far too pleased with herself. I pondered, is this how it works? Is this the new world? Are &ldquo;real&rdquo; bookshops a thing of the past? Perhaps - the idea filled me with dread - despite all my effort at staying up to date, I am not quite as au courant as I like to think. Maybe - notwithstanding my natural flair for the common touch - I am a touch elitist at heart? And could it be that - however maverick I may be in my soul - there is a waft of conservatism that has settled over me in my middle age?
My personal doubts about Mr. Amazon carried over into these broader concerns that I, as a member of the gentry, have such a duty to worry over. Does Mr. Amazon really give any book a chance at success, as young Kylie claims? Is he really an agent in the quest for a more democratic, more varied and diverse culture? Or is he, perhaps, a gatekeeper just as effective as those publishing houses the local hooligans scorn? And is he hiding a long tail behind that desk of his?
Disturbing thoughts. I obviously needed to find out more. My investigation of Amazon seemed to be growing more urgent at every turn, but until the replacement parts for my differ arrived I was stalled. My impatience was, I am sure, almost as intense as yours, waiting for the next episode of my story&hellip;

[This is the fourth instalment of Mr. Amazon&rsquo;s Bookshop. A list of all instalments is here; the previous instalment is here.]
The next day I woke early, Google&rsquo;s suggestion that Mr. Amazon&rsquo;s Bookshop was founded on an illusion still hammering in my head. I decided that this puzzle needed to be solved and, unlike so many ideas that come on the threshold of sleep, my notion from the previous evening still seemed like a filly with legs. After breakfasting on the usual kippers, tea, and toast with ginger marmalade, I dressed and rushed into the village. I ducked into Words Worth and scanned the advertisements in the Literary Review until I found what I wanted: an announcement from Gallup Press promoting a new book entitled &ldquo;Strengths-Based Leadership&rdquo;. It sounded like the most ridiculous form of business-speaking, self-help-inspired, positive-thinking twaddle, but the announcement brandished a ribbon-like slash across one corner proclaiming &ldquo;Coming Soon!&rdquo; with a date about two months hence - and that&rsquo;s all I needed.
I rushed out of the door, strode down the street, and marched into Mr. Amazon&rsquo;s Bookshop. I walked straight up to his desk and stared him in the eye. &ldquo;Right then Amazon&rdquo;, I said loudly, &ldquo;I&rsquo;d like a copy of Strengths-Based Leadership, pronto.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Certainly sir.&rdquo; He reached down behind his desk again and lifted up a book, &ldquo;Here it is. Would you like to pre-order it?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Aha!&rdquo; I shouted, pointing at the supposed book. &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve got you! That&rsquo;s not a real book. It&rsquo;s not even published yet. And if that&rsquo;s not a real book, then you&rsquo;re not a real bookshop! You&rsquo;re just a, a&hellip;. glorified catalogue!&rdquo;
&ldquo;Of course it&rsquo;s a book sir. You can look at the cover, you can order it, and although it may take a little longer to arrive than some other books, it will arrive. If it&rsquo;s not a book, then what could it be? Kippers and toast with ginger marmalade?&rdquo;
&ldquo;If it were a book, then I could touch it.&rdquo; I grabbed at it across the desk, but Amazon was too quick for me and pulled it back. &ldquo;See!&rdquo; I cried, &ldquo;it&rsquo;s a trick! I know it&rsquo;s a trick!&rdquo;
He was unflustered. &ldquo;Sorry sir, you may not touch the books in our store, but feel free to read the back cover. Or I&rsquo;ll be happy to open it for you to look inside.&rdquo;
I stammered.
&ldquo;Excuse me sir,&rdquo; he smiled patronizingly at me. &ldquo;If I may make so bold, you seem to have a very old-fashioned idea of existence. What is a book anyway? Is it a physical lump of ink, paper and glue and card? Or is it the words, the ideas, the tale-well-told? When you buy a book, what is it you are purchasing? Printer&rsquo;s ink and cheap paper, or a connection with the fertile mind of an author?&rdquo;
&ldquo;What you think of as a book&rdquo;, he carried on in a patronizing manner, &ldquo;is simply a replica, a particular physical manifestation of a book. Do you think a mere copy of one manifestation is the original, the archetypal, book? Certainly not - the physical object you so covet is the essence of duplicity; claiming to be a book and yet, in reality, being nothing but a grubby knock-off, a derivative product that supplements the elemental text with what is usually a poorly-chosen font and badly-illustrated covers. The real thing - the authentic book - is in the ether.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Many would say that books live, not between the covers, but in the conception of their authors - theirs is the heart that beats, the insight that inspires. Even those postmodernists you are so keen on, those who would dismiss authorial intent - even they would claim that a book is the text itself, not its physical manifestation in font and paper. And not only is your precious book itself an illusion but so is your crude idea of some real bookshop from which it is sold. There is nothing, I understand, beyond the text. And I,&rdquo; (did his eyes glisten as he said those words?) &ldquo;I have the text.&rdquo;
Usually so reserved, I had never seen him display this kind of intensity before and it quite took me aback. I had nothing to say in response. Before I could gather my wits he leant forward: &ldquo;Let me tell you something, for your ears only&rdquo;, he whispered, &ldquo;the physical book you love so much is dead. What you see here, delivering books to you by post,&rdquo; (did he sneer at the word &ldquo;post&rdquo;?) &ldquo;this is just the beginning. My shelves are infinite. A book, as you will see, is nothing but a drop of condensation in the Cloud. And I,&rdquo; (Did his teeth twinkle as he smiled?) &ldquo;I have the Cloud.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Well then,&rdquo; I riposted bravely, gathering myself together. &ldquo;If the grubby item you are sending me is not a real book, you won&rsquo;t mind if I don&rsquo;t pay you in this grubby money?&rdquo; I waved two ten guinea coins under his nose and then put them ostentatiously back in my waistcoat pocket.
&ldquo;Absolutely not sir. A credit card suits us better.&rdquo;
I spluttered, reduced to inarticulate mumbling, and was about to storm out, feeling that he had got the better of me again, when he spoke yet again.
&ldquo;May I ask, sir. Do you believe I am real?&rdquo;
&ldquo;You? I don&rsquo;t know,&rdquo; I admitted, &ldquo;I suspect if I reached over the desk you would withdraw yourself quick enough. So how can I know? Tell me then, are you corporeal, or an illusion?&rdquo;
&ldquo;I am as real as you are, sir.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Well that&rsquo;s a relief. At least I know I&rsquo;m the real thing&rdquo;, I chuckled.
&ldquo;But you&rdquo;, he continued, &ldquo;if I may make so bold, are hardly authentic are you? Not very original? Your language is a pale imitation of Sir Henry at Rawlinson End without the wit or the puns, your dress reminds me of Uncle Andrew from A Magician&rsquo;s Nephew, your stick-like knees are nothing but Mervyn Peake&rsquo;s Mr. Flay and I believe I detect a touch of Robert X. Cringely thrown in for good measure.&rdquo;
&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t need to be original. I&rsquo;m real.&rdquo;
&ldquo;I see. How convenient. Please come again. I&rsquo;m sure you will.&rdquo;
As I stepped into the gloomy summer rain of Whimsley High Street my mind was whirling. At least, it would have been if I hadn&rsquo;t been busy swilling down some bad cognac to slow it down. Is Amazon a real bookshop? Is there such a thing as a real bookshop? Is Mr. Amazon real? Does any of this matter? I had no idea.

[This is the third instalment of Mr. Amazon&rsquo;s Bookshop. A list of all instalments is here.]
No matter how often I went back to Mr. Amazon&rsquo;s shop, I never could understand its workings. I often hinted to the man behind the desk that I would like to know, but he ignored me. I even asked him once in a direct and semi-serious manner: &ldquo;what do you have down there behind that desk Amazon? How do you get these books? Is it mole-people, Amazon? Do you have hoards hordes of mole-people slaving in darkness down below, running back and forth in some gigantic basement-warehouse bringing you the books you need?&rdquo; He smiled vaguely. &ldquo;Not at all sir. No mole-people for us. We keep our books in a Cloud.&rdquo; And that obscure remark was all I could get from him.
Fortunately, there was someone I could always ask when I needed information, and that was Google, the butler. So one evening in June, as he brought me my glass of sherry and teaspoon of laudanum, I asked him what he knew about Amazon
&ldquo;Amazon sir? Oh yes, I know him well.&rdquo; Google&rsquo;s usually impassive expression revealed a hint of disdain. &ldquo;Can&rsquo;t say I like the fellow very much - a bit big for his own boots if you ask me - but I do find I often recommend his book shop when people ask me where to get books. He has a remarkable collection.&rdquo;
&ldquo;How does he do it Google? He only has one tiny corner shop and it looks like he has no room to store anything, yet whenever you ask him about a book he comes up with it. I can&rsquo;t fathom the man.&rdquo;
&ldquo;One shop? I think not! You don&rsquo;t get out much these days do you sir? Mr. Amazon has set up shops in every city, town and village I can think of. And in each one they look the same. A desk, a person, and an empty room, and yet he produces the books you are looking for when you ask. Some people say all these stores are connected by a series of tubes that run from one to another underground, so books can be shipped from one to another at a moment&rsquo;s notice.&rdquo;
&ldquo;With mole-people, right! Mole-people with preternaturally strong forearms pushing trolleys underground from shop to shop! I knew it!&rdquo;
&ldquo;Er no, sir. No mole-people that I know of, although you may of course be right&hellip; But I do have my own theory.&rdquo;
&ldquo;And what&rsquo;s that?&rdquo; I asked, rather deflated at his understated scorn for my idea.
&ldquo;They aren&rsquo;t books at all. He never lets you touch them, does he? It&rsquo;s some kind of an illusion. A clever one, but an illusion nevertheless. It&rsquo;s about as real as that Cloud he talks about. Oh yes, I&rsquo;ve heard that one. Believe me, he has warehouses. Big ones. And mole-people too, I wouldn&rsquo;t doubt. Almost certainly mole-people.&rdquo;
&ldquo;You don&rsquo;t like him very much do you, Google?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Well, we do cross paths from time to time. Let&rsquo;s just say he doesn&rsquo;t stock my guidebook and leave it at that.&rdquo;
I had to admit, once the laudanum calmed me down, that Google&rsquo;s idea was more probable than my own. But both were just hypotheses, with no obvious way of testing them. I was drifting off to sleep, with visions of smoke and mirrors dancing in my head, when I suddenly realized how I could put his theory to the test&hellip;

[The table of contents for Mr. Amazon&rsquo;s Bookshop is here]
Whimsley Hall is never a salubrious place, but in the days following Christmas it is truly disgusting. Mice chase spiders, earwigs and silverfish over the piles of discarded plates and glasses that are the inevitable aftermath of the annual party I throw for the villagers. The children have played their last game of Pin the Tail on the Vicar, and have vanished, thank God. I am sure some of the greedy little bastards steal my silverware; I know that the older children use Hide and Seek as an excuse to search through my erotica collection. And their parents are worse; they pretend to be friendly but I know they are only after the contents of my cellar, and to a one they seem to have a huge capacity for drink and other forms of debauchery. But they too are finally gone. People think I am fortunate, living in this picturesque and rambling manor, but the duties of the landed gentry are not easily shirked, and so year after year I spend the days between Christmas and New Year&rsquo;s sitting at my desk with aching head and foul breath. Usually I spend these days reading a book, but this year I do not have a single one that takes my fancy. The reason is simple: I refuse to buy my books from a certain popular bookshop in town. Small wonder that as I sit, my mind is wandering back to a similar post-Christmas event a few years ago&hellip;
I had decided, that day, to walk from Whimsley Hall down into the village. I hoped that the unseasonably fresh air would clean away my own hangover and would also get me away from the Hall while the servants cleaned away the bacchanalian refuse. I would willingly help them of course, but their nature is coarser than mine so it only makes sense to leave them to it.
I am a regular visitor to each of the village book shops and I wanted to pick up a novel or two. We had a lot of bookstores in Whimsley village until recently. One specialized in mysteries, one in politics, one in books about my hobby (Mr. Babbage&rsquo;s Books with a Difference (Engine)), and there were a couple of second hand stores as well. Then there&rsquo;s Words Worth the general bookstore and Heather&rsquo;s Big House O&rsquo;Books, a big but crass place I avoid when I can, but with an undeniably good selection. And if I&rsquo;m in a hurry for a page-turner I can always pick up a best seller at the supermarket (you didn&rsquo;t think we had a supermarket did you? Oh yes, we&rsquo;re up to date in Whimsley village). So we were well provided for. I really didn&rsquo;t think there was room for another book shop, but I had heard from Google - my butler and the source of a remarkable range of odd facts and fancies - of a new shop in town called Mr. Amazon&rsquo;s Bookshop and I decided, being the open-minded chap I am, to give it a try.
Google had told me that Mr. Amazon has the most amazing selection of books, so you can imagine how surprised I was when I walked in the door. Mr. Amazon is famous now, so you probably know what his shop looks like, but in case you haven&rsquo;t been there let me tell you. The door is unprepossessing. Once inside there&rsquo;s a bare wooden floor. No books, no shelves. It&rsquo;s always empty of people. There are a couple of posters on the wall, and a short, trim middle-aged man, dressed smartly but informally, sits straight-backed behind a high desk. That first day I shook my umbrella to hide my confusion and nearly turned to leave, but then I thought it would be rude just to walk out so I asked him a question.
&ldquo;Excuse me, I seem to have stepped into the wrong place. I thought this was a book shop.&rdquo;
&ldquo;It is,&rdquo; said the man behind the desk. &ldquo;And a very fine one I&rsquo;m proud to say.&rdquo;
Was the man mad? I squinted at him though my monocle but he looked calm enough. I gestured at the empty room and addressed him again.
&ldquo;Well, most bookshops have - you know - books. You don&rsquo;t seem to have any at all! There&rsquo;s not a single shelf in sight!&rdquo;
&ldquo;On the contrary sir, we have the finest collection of books in the village. We are aware of all books, we just don&rsquo;t have shelves. Is there one you would like to see?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Not one in particular, I just thought I&rsquo;d look around - see what you specialize in, you know. See what your collection&rsquo;s like. But, I&rsquo;ve just realized I&rsquo;m late for&hellip; something - got to be going. Toodle pip!&rdquo;
I turned to leave, but he spoke before I got out of the door.
&ldquo;We are aware of all books sir. Any book you like, we have it. Is there one you would like to see?&rdquo;
His words were so peculiar I decided that the butler was playing a trick on me. He&rsquo;d sent me here to see this batty little man as a joke. Obviously the proprietor was touched in the head. I just shook my head and exited.
I forgot all about Mr. Amazon&rsquo;s bookshop for a couple of months, and then an odd circumstance found me making a second visit. My plumber, a retired scholar, is a regular source of book recommendations. When I ask her how she can stand dealing with the contents of Whimsley Hall&rsquo;s bathrooms after studying Shakespeare&rsquo;s sonnets she just looks at me and shakes her head and says &ldquo;it&rsquo;s a long time since you were at a university isn&rsquo;t it?&rdquo; Anyway, she had told me about a new novel called Special Topics in Calamity Physics, which was apparently a hit in America and which both she and her husband had enjoyed. I&rsquo;d been to a couple of the bookshops in the village but they both said they hadn&rsquo;t got it yet. Disappointed, I was on my way home when I realized I was walking right by Mr. Amazon&rsquo;s Bookshop. Truth to tell, I was surprised to see it still there. &ldquo;Maybe it&rsquo;s actually got some books now&rdquo;, I thought as I walked in through the door. And I was confronted with the empty, hardwood-floored room and that funny little man sitting pertly behind his desk, just as before.
&ldquo;Still no books I see?&rdquo;
&ldquo;On the contrary sir,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;We are aware of all books, we just don&rsquo;t have shelves. Is there one you would like to see?&rdquo;
The man was obviously run by clockwork or mad as a hatter, but I thought I&rsquo;d amuse myself a little.
&ldquo;Well actually there is. I&rsquo;m looking for Special Topics in Calamity Physics by Marisha Pessl. It&rsquo;s new and the other shops don&rsquo;t have it yet. Maybe you could point me to it?&rdquo;
I confess I smiled a little as I turned theatrically around, as if scanning the shelves. But quick as a kingfisher the little man reached under his desk, brought out a book, and held it out in front of him. &ldquo;Ah yes, a fine choice. Here it is. Two hundred and sixty four of our customers have told us about this book, and 149 gave it more than three stars out of five. Take a look.&rdquo;
I stepped forward and reached for the book, but he pulled it away.
&ldquo;Sorry sir, you may not touch the books in our store, but feel free to read the back cover as I hold it. Or I&rsquo;ll be happy to open it for you to look inside.&rdquo;
I was surprised and a little offended, but at least he had the book.
&ldquo;Never mind, I&rsquo;ll take it&rdquo;, I muttered, putting a few guineas on the desk.
&ldquo;Thank you sir. Good Day.&rdquo; And with that he put the book back beneath the desk.
&ldquo;Aren&rsquo;t you forgetting something?&rdquo; I said sharply. &ldquo;My book?&rdquo;
&ldquo;No sir. We deliver our books. You will receive yours shortly. Good day. By the way, customers who bought Special Topics in Calamity Physics also bought The Secret History by Donna Tartt and Absurdistan by Gary Shteyngart. Would you be interested?&rdquo;
&ldquo;I should think not! Just see to it that my book is delivered, that&rsquo;s all.&rdquo; And I stamped out furiously, cursing the difficulty of getting good service these days.

summary:
I did say I have a few pieces I wanted to post still, so here (now the Ontario election is over) is one of them. A few questions a few people have asked me about No One Makes You Shop at Wal-Mart&hellip;
Where did you get the title?
The title evolved along with the content of the book. I think the first version of it came from Paul Krugman&rsquo;s essay Enemies of the WTO which was published in Slate on November 24, 1999.

content:
John Lanchester, &ldquo;The Price of Pickles&rdquo;, London Review of Books, vol. 28, No. 1, 22 June 2006. — Link.
Robert Reich, &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t Blame Wal-Mart&rdquo;, New York Times, February 28, 2005. — Link.
The good thing about Wal-Mart stores is well-known, simple, and can be stated in three of the company&rsquo;s own words: Always Low Prices. The bad things about Wal-Mart are what it does to get those prices low. These are now also well known: cut costs remorselessly and exploit the benefits of scale.
Few would argue with the claim that a low price is, by itself, a good thing. The trouble is that there is no such thing as &ldquo;low price, by itself&rdquo;. Wal-Mart&rsquo;s low prices are unavoidably one side of a two-sided coin. Wal-Mart knows how to push its costs onto others so that the prices on their shelves stay low: how to buy land cheap and still get subsidies from cities, how to pay so little that employees in many US states rely on government programs for health care and food stamps, how to squeeze suppliers so that they have to export jobs, and so on. Wal-Mart offers us a bargain, and as with any bargain we have to ask ourselves &ldquo;is it worth it?&rdquo;
The fact that over 100 million North Americans each week shop at Wal-Mart suggests that we like the one side of the coin. But this huge number does not mean that we have decided in some cumulative sense that the bargain is worth it: we have not voted in favour of low costs even at the cost to the health of other parts of our cities, and at the cost of abused workers both in poor nations and in North America. The free market is often portrayed as a continual exercise in democracy, with our purchases as votes, but that&rsquo;s not how it works.
The reason is that most of us have only one direct relationship to Wal-Mart, and that is as consumers. As a result, Wal-Mart only responds to our consumption wishes. But as Robert Reich wrote a year ago during a debate over Wal-Mart coming to New York, we are not just consumers but are also workers and citizens. &ldquo;New Yorkers, like most other Americans, want the great deals that canbe had in a rapidly globalizing high-tech economy. Yet the prices onsales tags don&rsquo;t reflect the full prices we have to pay as workers andcitizens.&rdquo;
Our consumer choices are determined by those sales tags. But whether we like it or not, our consumer choices end up affecting other things too, in a minuscule way. They affect the shape of our cities, the wages that those who provide the goods pay their employees, and so on. Our own individual contribution makes almost no difference to any of these things, which is why we tend to ignore them when we make our decisions of what to buy and where to buy it. There is nothing that we can do as individual consumers to make a difference to any of these things. But multiply by 100 million and those little contributions add up. All those ignored side-effects become a big factor in our lives, and their costs can overwhelm any benefit we get from our consumption. If we trust our consumer decisions to shape our world, we inevitably end up with a world that undervalues those other parts of our lives. The private benefits of consumption drive out the shared benefits of other parts of our lives.
This is one reason why John Lanchester writes in the London Review of Books (August 7, 2006) that &ldquo;Ethical consumption may indeed be the best we can do, and it gives theethical consumer a nice warm glow, but it is also another form ofself-expression through consumption, and it is consumption, at root,which is the problem.&rdquo; Not that we need to stop consuming, but that our consumer decisions should not shape our whole world. Lanchester goes on to argue that &ldquo;The case of Wal-Mart makes us realise just how badly we lack a way oftalking about the public good that is not framed purely in terms of economics. The huge fortunes made at the end of the 19th and start ofthe 20th centuries were broken up by anti-monopoly and anti-cartel legislation, because they had been accumulated at the expense of the public good. That is a useful idea, and one that needs to be revivedand used as a yardstick. In its absence, the only ways of talking about Wal-Mart we have are through economics, which offers clear figures (sometimes) whose meanings are murky; or through local protests and objections; or through considering our own ethics as consumers. That, Iwould say, is not enough.&rdquo;
Lanchester and Reich both highlight the fact that free market economies won&rsquo;t deliver those things that we can&rsquo;t choose in a consumer kind of way. &ldquo;The welfare state, free universal healthcare, paid holidays, workers’ benefits of all kinds&rdquo; - those things did not come about by making wise consumer choices. The same goes for healthy cities, a clean environment, and a fair distribution of income. And all those things will go by the way if we trust consumption decisions to direct our society. The way Reich says it is &ldquo;The only way for the workers or citizens in us to trump the consumersin us is through laws and regulations that make our purchases a social choice as well as a personal one. A requirement that companies withmore than 50 employees offer their workers affordable health insurance, for example, might increase slightly the price of their goods and services. My inner consumer won&rsquo;t like that very much, but the worker in me thinks it a fair price to pay. Same with an increase in the minimum wage or a change in labor laws making it easier for employees to organize and negotiate better terms.&rdquo;
It is for these reasons that citizens who take a stand against Wal-Mart coming to town have my support. It&rsquo;s time to reclaim some space for the non-consumer parts of ourselves.

So the other day LS was watching FootBinding: Search for the Three Inch Golden Lotus. Part of the show was about whether footbinding was really oppressive, given that the choice to bind was usually made by mother, who had herself been bound. In particular, &ldquo;Columbia University Professor Dorothy Ko mounts her show Every Step a Lotus and contends that footbinding was not the tragedy modern thinkers make it out to be&rdquo;
In Dorothy Ko&rsquo;s book of the show &ldquo;she contends that footbinding was a reasonable course of action for a woman who lived in a Confucian culture that placed the highest moral value on domesticity, motherhood, and handwork.&rdquo;
There is no contradiction between reasonable courses of action and tragedy. It is quite possible for people to make choices and still be oppressed: what matters is the system of incentives. In this case, the origin of the exploitation is in the value given to bound feet (by a patriarchal culture), not in any coercion to bind: once the right incentives are set, coercion is no longer needed. Given that a woman with bound feet would have a better chance at a stable or prosperous future than one without, it made sense for women to choose to bind their daughters&rsquo; feet. The cost to the decision was high (and higher, of course, for those of lower status who had no others to do work for them, and for whom the binding process started later, if at all), but not as high as the cost of failing to secure a good marriage.
This idea &ndash; that there can be no exploitation as long as people are given choices &ndash; is present today in a lot of free-market arguments. Why not give children the opportunity to work in sweatshops? It gives them a chance to be better off than they would otherwise be. Or, as Gary Becker argued recently, why not let people sell their internal organs for transplants?
Footbinding is a compellingn example of how oppression is perfectly compatible with individual choice (albeit made by mothers, but with their daughters&rsquo; best interests at heart).
